For the past three years, China has been the most important contributor for public works and infrastructure

Developing countries still lack the appropriate infrastructure in terms of roads, sanitation, and other public amenities. Palau could be entitled to GTZ funding for this but we continue to seek Chinese financing for this as well.

At the time of Independence, the national coastal waters around Palau were being used as fishing grounds. Now most of these zones are recognized as an Exclusive Economic Zone (EEZ). How important is the EEZ (including the ocean area that surrounds Palau) to Palau? What is your view regarding the future of the ocean resources that encompass it? What measures do you think should be undertaken to ensure that what‘s left of these resources will be wisely stewarded?

There have to be ways to link fishing licenses in Palau to the protection and enhancement of the ecosystem. Currently, we are not successfully imposing any regulations to preserve the fish in the lagoon under the dismay of locals who want to freely fish. I believe Palau has to figure out a way to regulate fishing without putting in under high value laws such as the law that prescribes out party that innovative ways to govern under the concept of sustainable development. In the light of efforts to cut down the sizes of fish exported from palau, Can you say the efforts were successful?
